&lt;p&gt;P =&amp;nbsp;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\({x^2}y\)&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;Q =&amp;nbsp;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(- x{y^2}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(\frac{{\partial Q}}{{\partial x}} = - {y^2}\)&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(\frac{{\partial P}}{{\partial y}} = {x^2}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Then using green&amp;rsquo;s theorem our line integral becomes&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\({\int\limits_{C}{Pdx+Qdy=\int\!\!\!\int\limits_{D}{\left({{{\partial Q}\over{dx}}-{{\partial P}\over{dy}}}\right)dA=}}\int\!\!\!\int\limits_{D}{-y^{2}-x^{2}dA=-\int\!\!\!\int\limits_{D}{(x^{2}+y^{2})dA}}}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(= {-\int\!\!\!\int\limits_{D}{(y^{2}+x^{2})dA=-\int\limits_{0}^{2\pi}{\int\limits_{0}^{2}{r^{2}.rdrd\theta}}}}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\( \Rightarrow  - \int\limits_0^{2\pi } {\left[ {\left( {\frac{{{r^4}}}{4}} \right)_0^2} \right]} d\theta  =  - \int\limits_0^{2\pi } {\left[ 4 \right]} d\theta  =  - \left( {4\theta } \right)_0^{2\pi } =  - 8\pi \)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;z = e&lt;sup&gt;x&lt;/sup&gt;siny &amp;rArr;&amp;nbsp;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(\frac{{\partial z}}{{\partial x}} = {e^x}siny\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(\frac{{\partial z}}{{\partial y}} = {e^x}cosy\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;x = log&lt;sub&gt;e&lt;/sub&gt;t &amp;rArr;&amp;nbsp;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(\frac{{dx}}{{dt}} = \frac{1}{t}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;and y = t&lt;sup&gt;2 &lt;/sup&gt;&amp;rArr;&amp;nbsp;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(\frac{{dy}}{{dt}} = 2t\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(\frac{{dz}}{{dt}} = \frac{{\partial z}}{{\partial x}}.\frac{{dx}}{{dt}} + \frac{{\partial z}}{{\partial y}}.\frac{{dy}}{{dt}}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(\frac{{{e^x}}}{t}(siny + 2{t^2}cosy)\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Concept&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Since we are required to find the line integral through a closed path, we can apply Green&amp;#39;s&amp;nbsp;theorem.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Green&amp;#39;s Theorem states that the line integral around a closed path equals the surface integral and is calculated as follows:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(\int\limits_C {Pdx + Qdy} = \iint\limits_D {(\frac{{\partial Q}}{{\partial x}} - \frac{{\partial P}}{{\partial y}})dA}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Calculation&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(P = {x^2}y\)&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;,&amp;nbsp;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(Q =- x{y^2}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(\frac{{\partial Q}}{{\partial x}} = - {y^2}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(\frac{{\partial P}}{{\partial y}} = {x^2}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Then using green&amp;rsquo;s theorem our line integral becomes:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(\int\limits_C {Pdx + Qdy} = \iint\limits_D {(\frac{{\partial Q}}{{\partial x}} - \frac{{\partial P}}{{\partial y}})dA = \iint\limits_D { - {y^2} - {x^2}dA = - \iint\limits_D {({x^2} + {y^2})dA}}}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(- \iint\limits_D {({y^2} + {x^2})dA}\)&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;=&amp;nbsp;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(- \int\limits_0^{2\pi } {\int\limits_0^2 {{r^2}.rdrd\theta } }\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(- \int\limits_0^{2\pi } {\int\limits_0^2 {{r^2}rdrd\theta } } = -8\pi\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;let z =&amp;nbsp;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(\frac{{1 + xtan x}}{x}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(\frac{{dz}}{{dx}} = - \frac{1}{{{x^2}}} + {\sec ^2}x\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(\frac{{{d^2}z}}{{d{x^2}}} = \frac{2}{{{x^3}}} + 2{\sec ^2}x\tan x\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(\frac{{dz}}{{dx}} = 0\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So we will get&amp;nbsp;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(x = \operatorname{cosx}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\({(\frac{{{d^2}z}}{{d{x^2}}})_{x = \cos x}} = 2se{c^3}x + 2{\sec ^2}x\tan x &amp;gt; 0\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Thus z has a minima and therefore y has a maxima at x = cosx&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Concept&lt;/u&gt;:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;f(z) = a&lt;sub&gt;0&lt;/sub&gt; + a, (z - a) + a&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt; (z - a)&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt; + &amp;hellip;+a&lt;sub&gt;-1&lt;/sub&gt; (z - a)&lt;sup&gt;-1&lt;/sup&gt;&amp;hellip;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The coefficient of (z &amp;ndash; a)&lt;span style=&quot;position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; top: -0.5em;&quot;&gt;-1&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;in the expansion of f(z) around on isolated singularity is called the residue of f(z) at that point.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Thus, the Laurent series expansion of f(z) around z = a,&amp;nbsp;i.e.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The residue of f(z) at z = a is a&lt;sub&gt;-1&lt;/sub&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Application&lt;/u&gt;:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Given:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(f\left( z \right) = z\cos \frac{1}{z}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;z = 0 is the only singularity since the Laurent series expansion about z = 0 is:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(z\cos \frac{1}{z} = z\left( {1 - \frac{1}{{2!{z^2}}} + \frac{1}{{4!{z^4}}} + \ldots } \right)\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(= z - \frac{1}{{2z}} + \frac{1}{{24{z^3}}} + \ldots \)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The residue of&amp;nbsp;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(\left( {z~\cos \frac{1}{z}} \right)\)&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;= coefficient of&amp;nbsp;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(\frac{1}{z}\)&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;in Laurent series.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;there4; Residue =&amp;nbsp;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(= \frac{{ - 1}}{2}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;we have P(r) =&amp;nbsp;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(\frac{{{m^r}{e^{ - m}}}}{{r!}}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;P(0)=e&lt;sup&gt;-m&lt;/sup&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;P(2)=&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(\frac{{{e^{ - m}}{m^2}}}{{2!}}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Required probability:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;P(0) + P(2) =&amp;nbsp;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\({e^{ - m}}(1 + \frac{{{m^2}}}{{2!}})\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

